2025-09-26 15:57:53,365 - INFO - Strategy Summary: Based on the experimental data, the best performance was observed in the first trial, where the deviation and variability were the lowest. This performance was achieved with an aspirate speed of 11 uL/s, dispense speed of 10 uL/s, aspirate wait time of 22.48 seconds, dispense wait time of 5.53 seconds, retract speed of 8.71 uL/s, pre-aspirate air volume of 0.076 mL, post-aspirate air volume of 0.036 mL, and overaspirate volume of 0.025 mL.

Patterns observed:
1. Lower aspirate and dispense speeds seem to correlate with lower deviation. 
2. Longer aspirate wait times and shorter dispense wait times also seem beneficial. 
3. Lower retract speeds may contribute to lower variability. 
4. Higher pre-aspirate air volume and lower post-aspirate air volume appear beneficial. 

Based on these observations, the following parameter combinations are recommended:

